class Solution:
    def maxDistance(self, colors: List[int]) -> int:
        n = len(colors)
        # Candidate 1: farthest from left endpoint
        left_color = colors[0]
        rightmost_diff = -1
        for i in range(n):
            if colors[i] != left_color:
                rightmost_diff = i
        dist1 = rightmost_diff if rightmost_diff != -1 else 0
        
        # Candidate 2: farthest from right endpoint
        right_color = colors[n - 1]
        leftmost_diff = n
        for i in range(n - 1, -1, -1):
            if colors[i] != right_color:
                leftmost_diff = i
        dist2 = (n - 1 - leftmost_diff) if leftmost_diff != n else 0
        
        return max(dist1, dist2)

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
The maximum distance between two houses with different colors must include at least one of the two endpoints of the array (index 0 or index n-1). This is because extending any internal pair toward an endpoint (while keeping different colors) cannot decrease the distance.

We therefore compute only two candidate distances:

1. Distance from index 0 to the rightmost house whose color differs from colors[0].
2. Distance from index n-1 to the leftmost house whose color differs from colors[n-1].

The answer is the larger of these two values. (If the whole array is the same color the problem guarantees this never happens.)

Both candidates are found with a single forward pass and a single backward pass, guaranteeing O(n) time.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
